.TH "sugarconvdsk" "1" "2026-03-28" "SugarConvDsk 1.0.216 User Manual" ""
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
sugarconvdsk - convert Amstrad CPC disk image formats
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]sugarconvdsk\f[R] \f[I]source\f[R] [\f[I]destination\f[R]]
[\f[B]-s=\f[R]_side_] [\f[B]-second=\f[R]_path_]
[\f[B]-o=\f[R]_outputformat_] [\f[B]-r\f[R]] [\f[B]-f=\f[R]_filter_]
.PP
\f[B]sugarconvdsk\f[R] \f[B]-cat=\f[R]_user_ [\f[B]-sort\f[R]]
[\f[B]-l\f[R]] [\f[B]-c\f[R]] \f[I]source\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]SugarConvDsk\f[R] converts Amstrad CPC disk dump files between
various formats.
It supports a wide range of input and output formats including DSK,
EDSK, HFE, IPF, SCP, CT-RAW, and Kryoflux.
.PP
When the \f[B]-cat\f[R] option is not used, \f[B]sugarconvdsk\f[R]
performs a format conversion.
When \f[B]-cat\f[R] is used, it displays the disk directory contents
without performing any conversion; in that case, \f[I]destination\f[R]
and all conversion flags are ignored.
.PP
Internally, the tool converts any supported format into an MFM-based
representation that handles weak bits, optional bits, and
multi-revolution tracks, then writes it back in the chosen output
format.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Conversion mode
.TP
\f[B]-s=\f[R]_side_
Select the disk side to convert.
\f[I]side\f[R] must be \f[B]1\f[R] or \f[B]2\f[R].
If omitted, both sides are written (where relevant for the chosen
format).
.TP
\f[B]-second=\f[R]_path_
Replace the second side of the disk with the dump source file at
\f[I]path\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]-o=\f[R]_outputformat_
Select the output format.
Accepted values:
.RS
.PP
\f[B]EDSK\f[R] \[em] Extended DSK format (default), \f[B]HFE\f[R] \[em]
HFE format, \f[B]IPF\f[R] \[em] Interchangeable Preservation Format,
\f[B]SCP\f[R] \[em] Supercard Pro format.
.PP
If omitted, the default output format is EDSK.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]-r\f[R]
If \f[I]source\f[R] is a directory, convert files recursively.
.TP
\f[B]-f=\f[R]_filter_
If \f[I]source\f[R] is a directory, apply a filename filter
(e.g.\ **[CPC]*.dsk**).
.SS Catalog mode
.TP
\f[B]-cat=\f[R]_user_
Display the disk directory for the given CP/M \f[I]user\f[R] number
(0\[en]15).
Use \f[B]ALLUSERS\f[R] to display entries for all users.
This option prevents any conversion from taking place.
.TP
\f[B]-sort\f[R]
Sort the listed files in alphabetical order.
.TP
\f[B]-l\f[R]
Display one file per line.
Adds flag \f[B]H\f[R] for hidden files and \f[B]R\f[R] for read-only
files.
.TP
\f[B]-c\f[R]
Display files on a single line, separated by semicolons.
.SS General
.TP
\f[B]\[en]help\f[R]
Display a usage summary and exit.
.SH OPERANDS
.TP
\f[I]source\f[R]
Source disk image file or directory.
Supported input formats:
.RS
.PP
\f[B]CTRAW\f[R] \[em] CT-RAW format, \f[B]DSK\f[R] \[em] standard DSK
format, \f[B]EDSK\f[R] \[em] Extended DSK format, \f[B]HFE\f[R] \[em]
HFE format, \f[B]IPF\f[R] \[em] Interchangeable Preservation Format,
\f[B]SCP\f[R] \[em] Supercard Pro format, \f[B]KRYOFLUX\f[R] \[em]
Kryoflux RAW file set.
.PP
If \f[I]source\f[R] is a directory, every file in that directory is
converted and saved to the \f[I]destination\f[R] directory.
.RE
.TP
\f[I]destination\f[R]
Output file or directory.
If \f[I]source\f[R] is a directory, \f[I]destination\f[R] is used as the
output directory.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Convert a single file to IPF format:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sugarconvdsk disk.dsk output.ipf -o=IPF
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Recursively convert all **[CPC]*.dsk\f[B] files from \f[R]/dump\f[B] to
IPF, storing results in \f[R]/result**:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sugarconvdsk /dump /result -o=IPF -r -f=[CPC]*.dsk
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Display the directory of a disk image for CP/M user 0:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sugarconvdsk -cat=0 disk.dsk
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Display all users\[cq] files, sorted alphabetically, one per line:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sugarconvdsk -cat=ALLUSERS -sort -l disk.dsk
\f[R]
.fi
.SH BUGS
.PP
